      { question: "A 55-year-old woman on warfarin for a mechanical mitral valve (INR 2.8) is scheduled for elective total knee replacement in 7 days. What is the appropriate anticoagulation management plan?", options: ["Continue warfarin through surgery - the bleeding risk of holding it exceeds the thromboembolic risk", "Stop warfarin 5 days pre-op, bridge with therapeutic LMWH (enoxaparin 1 mg/kg BID), hold LMWH 24 hours before surgery, restart postoperatively when hemostasis is achieved", "Stop warfarin 2 days pre-op with no bridging needed for this indication", "Switch to aspirin 325 mg daily instead of warfarin for the perioperative period"], correct: 1, rationale: "Mechanical heart valves (especially mitral position) are a HIGH-risk indication for bridging anticoagulation. Warfarin should be stopped 5 days before surgery to allow INR to normalize. Bridging with therapeutic-dose LMWH (enoxaparin 1 mg/kg SC BID) is initiated when INR falls below the therapeutic range (usually 2-3 days before surgery). The last dose of therapeutic LMWH is held 24 hours before surgery. Postoperatively, bridging is restarted when surgical hemostasis is adequate (typically 24-48 hours post-op, in consultation with the surgical team), and warfarin is restarted concurrently. Bridging continues until the INR is therapeutic for 2 consecutive days." }
